  "text": "In the current study, age was found to be statistically correlated to chemotherapy induced amenorrhea as patients with older ages are more borne for permanent amenorrhea and ovarian failure while younger ages were more borne to transient amenorrhea with p value 0.0001, any authors have confirmed same results. [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] It is believed that regularity of menses is correlated with induction of amenorrhea post chemotherapy as detailed by 10 patients who had a Hodgkin's disease with irregular menses experienced longer amenorrhea period than those with regular one, in our study patients with regular menses had lower incidence of chemotherapy induced amenorrhea with p value 0.001 when compared to those with irregular menses. [CITATION_3] Our study was the first to find a statistically significant correlation between chronic disease as DM and CIA with p value 0.013 when compared to patients who didn't suffer from DM, nonetheless we discovered that patients who had CBS had lower rates of CIA, this may be due to younger women tend to have conservative surgeries to maintain the cosmetic contour of the breast while older women usually go for MRM to avoid adjuvant chemotherapy and postoperative radiation p value 0.001.",
